"Christian Ravius (1613-1677) was a German orientalist from Berlin. In 1651 he was together with other European humanists such as Claudius Salmasius, Nicholas Heinsius and Isaac Vossius invited to the court of Queen Christina of Sweden. He had in the 1630’s stayed in Constantinople with the celebrated English Arabist Ewdard Poccock and then held positions in the Netherlands and England. He was appointed professor of oriental languages at Uppsala University in 1651, where he kept his chair for eighteen years until 1669 with some interruption (1655-1659), when he also was royal librarian. Stiernhielm was acquainted with Ravius and they corresponded by letters.
Ravius advanced – in opposition to common opinion of his own time – the ground-breaking theory that all languages termed as Oriental (today Semitic), i.e. Hebrew, Chaldaic, Syriac, Samaritan, Arabic, and Ethiopic, are actually one and the same idiom. Ravius takes his point of departure from Aristotle’s classification of categories: the antithetical pair of concepts, or the dichotomy, of essence and accidence. The guiding idea is that the oriental languages are the same in essence, but differ in accidents, in the inflections of words and in the pronounciation etc. Ravius puts forward this view in his various treatises: Orthographiae et analogiae (vulgo etymologiae) Ebraicae delineatio (1646), A discourse concerning the Easterne tongues (1648), which was published in the same volume as his A general grammar for the ready attaining of Ebrew, Samaritan, Chalde, Syriac, Arabic and Ethiopic (1650). 
Below I have collected some passages that pinpoint how Ravius concept-ualized the unity of the Oriental, i.e. the Semitic languages. This has bearing on Stiernhielm’s conceptualization of linguistic relationship in general."
